{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d9cf0c05-6a4e-4ed1-86b0-2cdb5750eea6","content":"`dotnet-dump` is now installed and ready. Here's how to analyze your dump:\n\n### Quick Start\n\n```bash\n# Open interactive analysis session\ndotnet-dump analyze <path-to-your.dmp>\n```\n\n### Key Commands Once Inside\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` | Print last exception (start here!) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack for current thread |\n| `clrstack -all` | Stacks for all managed threads |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (memory issues) |\n| `gcroot <addr>` | Find what's keeping an object alive |\n| `exit` | Quit the analyzer |\n\n### Recommended Workflow\n1. **`pe`** — see the crashing exception + stack trace\n2. **`threads`** — find threads with exceptions\n3. **`clrstack`** on interesting threads — understand what was running\n4. **`dso`** — inspect objects on the stack for clues\n\nIf you can share the dump file path (or upload it to this environment), I can run these commands for you and help interpret the results.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"390cc0a4-d876-49ce-989b-5face31dfb5e","outputTokens":307,"requestId":"D806:33B14:22748C:282B3D:69F2B6B3"},"id":"2db52740-9c4b-4e98-adb1-d9080b5675e0","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:56:20.987Z","parentId":"82f3454c-1883-462d-b699-76a22a173803"}
